//Page 8
let numberOfRabbits = 101
/*:
When you define a constant in Swift, itâ€™s called _declaring_ a constant. So the statement above is known as a _declaration_. The instruction it gives to the computer is â€œDeclare that the name `numberOfRabbits` has the value `101`.â€

The word `let` is an example of a _keyword_. Each keyword has a special meaning in Swift and can't be used as a name.  The `let` keyword is used to declare a constant. Over time, youâ€™ll be introduced to more Swift keywords.

The last part of the statement, `= 101`, is where you _assign_ a value to the constant. This is called _assignment_ and the equal sign `=` is called the _assignment operator_.

 - Note: Donâ€™t worry about memorizing every new term - it can be overwhelming! Youâ€™ll see these terms used in context during the rest of the course, and you can always find them in the Glossary if you need to refresh your memory.

[Previous](@previous)  |  page 8 of 14  |  [Next: Wrapping Up](@next)
